Practical 1: Install, Configure and Run Hadoop & HDFS

Aim

Install Hadoop on Windows, configure Hadoop and HDFS, and verify that Hadoop services are running successfully.

Step 1: System Requirements
Component	Version
Windows	10/11 (64-bit)
Java	JDK 8
Hadoop	3.3.0
RAM	Minimum 8 GB (4 GB also works)
Disk Space	At least 10 GB free
Step 2: Software Required

Install these first:

Java JDK 8
Apache Hadoop 3.3.0
7-Zip
Winutils
Visual C++ Redistributable
Step 3: Install Java

Install Java JDK 8.

After installation, check it:

Open Command Prompt

java -version

Expected output:

java version "1.8.0_xxx"

Now check

javac -version

Expected output

javac 1.8.0_xxx

If both commands work, Java is installed correctly.

Step 4: Install Hadoop

Extract

hadoop-3.3.0.tar.gz

using 7-Zip.

After extracting, rename the folder to

C:\Hadoop

Your folder should look like

C:
│
├── Hadoop
│      ├── bin
│      ├── etc
│      ├── sbin
│      ├── share
│      ├── data
│      └── ...
Step 5: Install Winutils

Download Winutils.

Copy the bin folder into

C:\Hadoop

Replace the existing bin folder if prompted.

Step 6: Create Data Folders

Inside

C:\Hadoop

create

data

Inside data, create

namenode

and

datanode

Final structure

C:\Hadoop

│
├── data
│     ├── namenode
│     └── datanode
Step 7: Set Environment Variables

Open

Control Panel

↓

System

↓

Advanced System Settings

↓

Environment Variables

Create

JAVA_HOME
C:\Program Files\Java\jdk1.8.0_xxx

Create

HADOOP_HOME
C:\Hadoop

Edit Path

Add

%JAVA_HOME%\bin

Add

%HADOOP_HOME%\bin

Restart your computer after saving the changes.

Step 8: Configure Hadoop Files

Go to

C:\Hadoop\etc\hadoop
1. core-site.xml

Replace everything inside <configuration> with:

<configuration>
    <property>
        <name>fs.defaultFS</name>
        <value>hdfs://localhost:9000</value>
    </property>
</configuration>
2. hdfs-site.xml
<configuration>

<property>
<name>dfs.replication</name>
<value>1</value>
</property>

<property>
<name>dfs.namenode.name.dir</name>
<value>file:///C:/Hadoop/data/namenode</value>
</property>

<property>
<name>dfs.datanode.data.dir</name>
<value>file:///C:/Hadoop/data/datanode</value>
</property>

</configuration>
3. mapred-site.xml

Rename

mapred-site.xml.template

to

mapred-site.xml

Then paste

<configuration>

<property>
<name>mapreduce.framework.name</name>
<value>yarn</value>

</property>

</configuration>
4. yarn-site.xml

Paste

<configuration>

<property>
<name>yarn.nodemanager.aux-services</name>
<value>mapreduce_shuffle</value>
</property>

</configuration>

Note: Your manual contains typos such as mapreduce_shufle and ShufleHandler. Use mapreduce_shuffle as shown above for newer Hadoop versions.

Step 9: Configure hadoop-env.cmd

Open

hadoop-env.cmd

Find

JAVA_HOME=%JAVA_HOME%

or the JAVA_HOME setting and set it to your JDK path, for example:

set JAVA_HOME=C:\Program Files\Java\jdk1.8.0_XXX

Replace XXX with your installed JDK version.

Step 10: Format NameNode

Open Command Prompt as Administrator

Go to

cd C:\Hadoop\bin

Run

hdfs namenode -format

If successful, you'll see messages ending with something like:

Storage directory has been successfully formatted
Step 11: Start Hadoop

Go to

cd C:\Hadoop\sbin

Run

start-dfs.cmd

Then

start-yarn.cmd

or, if available in your setup,

start-all.cmd
Step 12: Check Running Services

Run

jps

You should see processes similar to:

NameNode
DataNode
ResourceManager
NodeManager
Jps
Step 13: Open Hadoop Web UI

Open your browser and go to:

http://localhost:9870

If the Hadoop dashboard opens, your installation is successful.

Expected Output
Java installed successfully.
Hadoop starts without errors.
jps lists Hadoop services.
The Hadoop web interface opens at http://localhost:9870.
